Cervical Spine Reconstruction with Chest Tube Technique After Metastasis 
Resection: A Single-Center Experience.

Wang Z(1), Yuh SJ(2), Renaud-Charest E(1), Tarabay B(2), Gennari A(2), Shedid 
D(2), Boubez G(1), Truong VT(3).

Author information:
(1)Division of Orthopedics, Centre Hospitalier de l'Université de Montréal, 
University of Montreal, Montreal, Quebec, Canada.
(2)Division of Neurosurgery, Centre Hospitalier de l'Université de Montréal, 
University of Montreal, Montreal, Quebec, Canada.
(3)Division of Orthopedics, Centre Hospitalier de l'Université de Montréal, 
University of Montreal, Montreal, Quebec, Canada. Electronic address: 
drtruongtri@gmail.com.

BACKGROUND: The silastic tube technique, in which a chest tube is placed into 
the vertebral body defect and impregnated with polymethyl methacrylate, showed 
good results in patients with lumbar and thoracic neoplastic diseases. There has 
been only 1 study about the effectiveness and safety of this technique in 
patients with cervical metastases. We aimed to report our experience in using 
this technique to reconstruct the spine after corpectomy for cervical 
metastasis.
METHODS: All patients with cervical spinal metastasis who underwent surgical 
treatment using a chest tube impregnated with polymethyl methacrylate in 
conjunction with anterior cervical plate stabilization were retrospectively 
recruited. Demographics, tumor histology, revised Tokuhashi score, preoperative 
and postoperative American Spinal Injury Association score, preoperative and 
postoperative ambulatory status, perioperative complications, and survival time 
were collected.
RESULTS: This study included 16 patients. The most common primary tumor site was 
the lung (6 patients; 37.5%). The mean (SD) survival time was 408 (795) days 
(range, 1-2797 days), and the median survival time was 72 days (95% confidence 
interval 28-116 days). Four patients (25%) died within 30 postoperative days. 
There was no surgical site infection or instrument failure after the surgery. 
Five patients (31.2%) lived >180 days, and 3 patients (18.8%) lived >360 days. 
One patient (6.2%) was still alive at the end of the study.
CONCLUSIONS: The silastic tube technique in conjunction with anterior cervical 
plate stabilization might be safe, effective, and cost-effective for patients 
with cervical spine metastasis.

